As of September 1, all student meals will be FREE until December 31, or until funds are no longer available. Breakfast and lunch will be free to anyone 18 years of age or under. In-Person students will receive theirs every day, with Friday's meal being sent home on Thursday. Remote learners as well as anyone else 18 years old and under can pick up 5 days worth of meals at JCHS every Friday between 11am-1pm. If your child is a remote learner or does not attend JCUSD #100, please fill out the survey below to ensure that our food service staff prepare the appropriate amount of meals on Fridays. In-Person learners do not need to complete this survey. Thank you!

https://forms.gle/iqQVgtGqcNjVimQK8

post_text:
We regret to inform you that this year’s performance of “Bye Bye Birdie,” originally scheduled for March 19-22, has officially been cancelled. We had hoped to reschedule the show for this summer, but this was not possible. Those who purchased tickets can either donate to the JCHS Theater Friends or request a refund.

Those who purchased tickets are advised to email byebyebirdie@jersey100.org with the direction to DONATE TO THEATER FRIENDS or REQUEST A REFUND. Please be sure to include name, address, phone number and number of tickets purchased.

We know many of you were looking forward to another spectacular performance, and the kids are heartbroken they will not be able to showcase all of their hard work. Thank you for supporting our Theatre Department!

post_text:
JCMS 5th grade students enjoy learning in the dark during glow day. Students in Mrs. Herkert, Mrs, Brady, Mrs, Egelhoff and Mrs. Evans rooms were glowing all day during Glow day.
In math, the kids did a CSI Whodunit activity. They had to solve equations involving multiplication of fraction and whole numbers. Based upon their answers, they were given clues to find out who committed the crime, where, and with what.
In ELA, students rotated between three stations. They sorted different cards into author’s purpose, identified text structures of two passages, and responded to comprehension questions after reading “The Science of Glow Sticks.”

post_text:
Mrs. Herkertś students worked on two social studies projects last week.
Students read about different land forms around the United States. They then created a poem about an explorer visiting different land forms. They chose to write it in either first person (they were the explorer) or third person.
Also, students read different passages about each of the Earth’s Systems - Hydrosphere, Atmosphere, Geo-sphere, Biosphere. They chose one system to create a poster to share with the class. Students had to draw and label 5 things found in their system, list a specific interaction with each of the other systems, and give 5 facts about it. Pairs/individuals presented these to the class to enhance comprehension of each of the systems.

Mrs. Herkertś students worked on two social studies projects last week.
Students read about different land forms around the United States. They then created a poem about an explorer visiting different land forms. They chose to write it in either first person (they were the explorer) or third person.
Also, students read different passages about each of the Earth’s Systems - Hydrosphere, Atmosphere, Geo-sphere, Biosphere. They chose one system to create a poster to share with the class. Students had to draw and label 5 things found in their system, list a specific interaction with each of the other systems, and give 5 facts about it. post_text: During the month of January, Mrs. Kuebrich's and Mrs. Durie's early childhood classrooms at West have been participating in several winter-themed lessons including: Listening to winter/snow books; making snowmen with Handwriting Without Tears pieces and with craft materials; measuring themselves to see how many "snowballs" tall they are; playing at winter-themed centers; and practicing taking turns during winter-themed games--check it out!

post_text: The Third and Fourth grade students teams from East Elementary and Grafton Elementary had a great day at the Olympiad. The Olympiad is a STEM competition between all the school in our region. Twenty nine different teams from our region competed today. East Elementary took 4 teams and Grafton Elementary took 1 team. Everyone had a lot of fun and even learned a lot. East Elementary came home with 3 places. They placed 1st, 3rd and 5th place! Way to go Jersey100!
